  "texts": [
    "I. INTRODUCTIONLarge Language Models (LLMs) have become a cornerstone in the advancement of natural language processing (NLP) and artificial intelligence (AI) technologies, offering unprecedented capabilities in language understanding, generation, and translation [1]- [3].",
    "LLMs, trained on vast datasets sourced from the internet, reflect and amplify the biases present in their training data, raising significant concerns about their fairness and the ethical implications of their deployment [4], [5].",
    "The inherent biases in LLMs can perpetuate and even exacerbate societal inequalities, making the examination of fairness and bias within these models not just a technical challenge, but a moral requirement [6]- [8].",
    "As LLMs become more integrated into societal frameworks, the urgency to address these biases becomes paramount, necessitating a thorough understanding of their nature, origins, and impacts [7]- [10].Despite the growing body of research on detecting and mitigating bias in LLMs, existing efforts often fall short in fully addressing the complexity of fairness and bias in these models.",
    "Studies highlighted the inadequacies in current methodologies for bias measurement and mitigation, pointing out that many Please contact the corresponding author, Man-Yee Chan: Chan-Man-Yee-HK@hotmail.com approaches fail to account for the sophisticated ways in which biases manifest across different contexts and cultures [11]- [16]."
